rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_I712077
rdf:Description.dcterms:description: TEV protease (N-terminal half) - entered sequence may be wrong
rdf:Description.igem:description:
N-terminal half of TEV (Tobacco Etch Virus) protease.
TEV protease is a highly site-specific protease that is found in the Tobacco Etch Virus (TEV). One of the main uses of this protease is for removing affinity tags from purified proteins. But scientists developed assay for detecting transmembrane protein interactions on its base.
TEV protease is splitted into halves (N-terminal and C-terminal). These halves are inactive but assembles and regain activity if they are fused with interacting transmembrane proteins. For detecting TEV protease activity another fusion protein is constructed which is composed of transmembrane region, specific TEV protease cleavage site and kind of transcription factor. When both halves of TEV protease assembles and therefore split protease regains activity it cleaves third protein and transcription factor is released from membrane. Transcription factor is later translocated to the nucleus where induces transcription of promoter with reporter gene.
This is N-terminal half of this protease.
rdf:Description.igem:author: Rok Gaber

rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_I742133
rdf:Description.dcterms:description: CrtIB genes with PstI site mutated out
rdf:Description.igem:description:
CrtIB encodes two enzymes, which make up steps three and two in the carotenoid biosynthesis pathway respectively.
CrtI encodes phytoene desaturase and CrtB encodes Phytoene synthase.
Both cloned genes still have their native ribosome binding sites.
More information about the carotenoid synthesis pathway may be found on the [http://parts.mit.edu/igem07/index.php/Edinburgh/Yoghurt/Design#Colour_Production Edinburgh Yoghurt Wiki]
rdf:Description.igem:author: sarah hollingshead
rdf:Description.igem:source:
Genes were both isolated from Pantoea ananatis (formerly Erwinia uredovora) DSMZ 30080, ATCC 19321
Diversity of Carotenoid Synthesis Gene Clusters from Environmental Enterobacteriaceae Strains, N Sedkova, APPLIED AND ENVIRONMENTAL MICROBIOLOGY, 71(12): 8141???8146 (2005)
Elucidation of Pathway the Erwinia uredovora Carotenoid Biosynthetic by Functional Analysis of Gene Products Expressed in Escherichia coli, N Misawa, et al, JOURNAL OF BACTERIOLOGY, 172(12): 6704-6712 (1990)
rdf:Description.igem:note: The CrtI gene contained two PstI sites, which were both mutated out using point mutagenesis

rdf:Description.dcterms:title: BBa_I742134
rdf:Description.dcterms:description: Recombinase XerC of the XerCD complex.
rdf:Description.igem:description:
Xer C is activated by a septum-translocated FtsK at cell division. It pairs with XerD to make an activated complex which cleaves or inverts sequences at dif-sites, depending on dif-site directionality. See Edinburgh project 2007 for details.
It turns out that XerC overexpression is a very effective way of not getting any colonies on your agar-plates. Therefore the Edinburgh 2007 team never incorperated it into its final construct.
rdf:Description.igem:author: Caroline Dahl
rdf:Description.igem:source: XerC is an innate E. coli K12 locus.
rdf:Description.igem:note: The coding XerC sequence contains none of the restriction sites used when biobricking.
